[1] Viet Nam, culling wild birds?
Date: Wed 30 Nov 2005
From: ProMED-mail <promed@promedmail.org>
Source: UPI via World Peace Herald, 30 Nov 2005 [edited]
<http://www.wpherald.com/storyview.php?StoryID=20051130-094831-2034r>

U.N.: Culling wild birds ineffective in stopping flu
-----------------------------------------------
The U.N. Food and Agriculture Organization (FAO) says controlling avian
influenza in poultry is the most effective public health measure.
Juan Lubroth, an FAO officer in charge of infectious animal diseases, said
culling wild birds is likely to be ineffective. Viet Nam has reportedly
begun attempting to cull birds in Ho Chi Minh City.
"Wild bird species found in and around cities are different from the
wetland waterfowl that have been identified as carriers of the avian
influenza virus," Lubroth said.
The FAO recommends improved veterinary services, emergency response and the
culling of domesticated fowl exposed to the disease as the most effective
means of controlling bird flu. More than 60 people have died of avian
influenza, mostly in Southeast Asia. So far, all humans infected appear to
have gotten the disease from domestic poultry.
--
ProMED-mail
<promed@promedmail.org>
